<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Proposed Special Conditions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Accordingly, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) proposes the following special conditions as part of the
type certification basis for the General Electric Aircraft Engines GE90 series turbofan engines. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(a) The following must be shown by tests and analyses, or other methods acceptable to the Administrator, that, in lieu
of the fan blade containment test with the fan blade failing at the point specified in &sect;33.94 paragraph (a) subparagraph
(1), a fan blade containment test with the fan blade failing at the inner flowpart diameter demonstrates: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) That the disk and fan blade retention system can withstand without failure a centrifugal load equal to two times
the maximum load which the engine could experience within approved operating limitations, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) That by a procedure approved by the Administrator an operating limitation must be established which specifies
the maximum allowable number of start-stop stress cycles for the fan blade retention system. The fan blade retention
system includes the portion of the fan blade from the inner flowpath diameter inward to the blade dovetail, the blade
retention components, and the fan disk and fan blade attachment features. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) It must be shown that the probability of fan blade retention system failure, for any cause, during the service life
of the engine to be extremely improbable. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) It must be shown by test or analysis that a lightning strike on the composite fan blade structure will not result
in a hazardous condition, and that the engine will meet the requirements of &sect;33.75. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) The tests and analyses required by (a)(1) and (a)(2) of these special conditions must account for the effects of
in-service deterioration, manufacturing and materials variations, and environmental effects. 
