SUPPLEMENTARY INFORMATION:
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Background
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
Air-over-hydraulic brake systems typically consist of an air brake system from the treadle valve to an air brake chamber
that provides the mechanical force to actuate a hydraulic-operated master cylinder. In turn, the hydraulic master
cylinder actuates the brake shoes or pads. The air brake chamber unit combined with the hydraulic-operated master
cylinder is called the ``power cluster'' and generally serves as the separating point between the air- and hydraulic-actuated
portions of the air-over-hydraulic brake system.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Air-over-hydraulic brake systems are installed on about one percent of medium and heavy trucks sold in the United
States. This percentage represents about 2,000 vehicles, most of which are Class 6 vehicles with gross vehicle weight
ratings (GVWRs) between 19,501 and 26,000 pounds.
