<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
Federal motor vehicle safety standard No. 121, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Air brake systems, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
currently defines ``air brake system'' to mean
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=20 g=1 f=1 -->
a system that uses air as a medium for transmitting pressure or force from the driver control to the service brake, but
does not include a system that uses compressed air or vacuum only to assist the driver in applying muscular force to
hydraulic or mechanical components. (49 CFR &sect;571.121)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=1 -->
Part 570, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=3 -->
Vehicle In Use Inspection Standards, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=1 -->
defines ``Air-over-hydraulic brake system'' to mean
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=20 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=20 g=1 f=3 -->
a subsystem of the air brake 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=20 g=1 f=1 -->
that uses compressed air to transmit a force from the driver control to a hydraulic brake system to actuate the service
brakes. (49 CFR Part 570, emphasis added)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 04 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=1 -->
The italic portion of the definition of air-over-hydraulic subsystem explicitly states that an air-over-hydraulic
brake subsystem means a subsystem of the air brake system.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
In initially issuing Standard No. 121, NHTSA stated that ``it should be noted that the term `air brake system' as defined
in the standard applies to the brake configuration commonly referred to as `air-over-hydraulic,' in which failure
of either medium can result in complete loss of braking ability.'' (36 FR 3817, February 27, 1971). The agency reiterated
its position that an air-over-hydraulic brake system is subject to Standard No. 121, stating that ``Standard No.
105a [Hydraulic Brake Systems] does not apply to vehicles equipped with `air-over-hydraulic' systems, which remain
within the purview of Standard No. 121*&blank;*&blank;*.'' (37 FR 17970, September 2, 1972.) Moreover, NHTSA has
issued several interpretations stating that a vehicle equipped with an air-over-hydraulic brake system must comply
with the requirements in Standard No. 121.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
NHTSA received a petition from Mr. John Kourik, requesting that the agency amend Standard No. 121 to specify that an
air-over-hydraulic brake subsystem is subject to that Standard. The petitioner stated that such an amendment would
avoid the need for manufacturers to request interpretations about air-over-hydraulic brake systems.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
After reviewing the petition, NHTSA has decided to propose amending Standard No. 121 by expanding the current definition
of air brake system to incorporate the definition of air-over-hydraulic brake subsystem. The agency notes that even
though the definition of an air brake system currently includes a description of an air-over-hydraulic subsystem,
it is not explicitly clear on the face of the standard that such a subsystem is classified as an air-braked system and
that a vehicle equipped with such a subsystem would thus have to comply with the requirements in Standard No. 121. NHTSA
believes that it would be appropriate to clarify the classification of air-over-hydraulic brake systems. By amending
the definition of an air brake system to state explicitly that an air-over-hydraulic brake subsystem is classified
as an air brake system, the agency would eliminate the need felt by some manufacturers to request interpretations
regarding the standard's applicability to vehicles equipped with air-over-hydraulic brake subsystems.
